25|$|The <b>electoral</b> <b>reforms</b> of {{the bull}} were not {{received}} well in all quarters. The precedent that only cardinal-bishops could vote in elections was met with disdain by the minor Roman clergy. The cardinal-bishops, because of their offices, were “distinctly non-Roman,” thus removing the control held by the Roman metropolitan church over {{the election of the}} pontiff.The bull was also a set back for the cardinal-priests and cardinal-deacons, from whom, in theory, the next pope had to be chosen from before the bull was issued.|$|E
